# Let's get some tweets in english containing the words "machine learning"
mach_tweets = searchTwitter("#machinelearning", n=200, lang="en")

# convert tweets to a data frame
machtweets.df <- twListToDF(mach_tweets)

#Extract the text from the tweets in a vector
mach_text = sapply(mach_tweets, function(x) x$getText())

#Construct the lexical Corpus and the Term Document Matrix
#function Corpus to create the corpus, and the function VectorSource to indicate that the text is in the character vector mach_text

mach_corpus = Corpus(VectorSource(mach_text))

## create document term matrix applying some transformations
MyCorpus <- tm_map(mach_corpus,
                   content_transformer(function(x) iconv(x, to='UTF-8-MAC', sub='byte')),
                   mc.cores=1)
tdm = TermDocumentMatrix(MyCorpus,control = list(removePunctuation = TRUE,stopwords = c("machine", "learning", "mine" ,"available", "http","httptcolfckhm" , "gold","via", "httptcoorybsin" ,"www" ,"can", "cant","change","will",stopwords("english")),removeNumbers = TRUE, tolower = TRUE))


## Part 1 inspect frequent words

(freq.terms <- findFreqTerms(tdm, lowfreq = 14))
##  [1] "analytics"       "azure"           "azureml"        
##  [4] "basics"          "beginners"       "bigdata"        
##  [7] "datascience"     "deeplearning"    "httptcoorybsin" 
## [10] "machinelearning" "quantum"         "rstats"         
## [13] "software"        "tutorial"
# which words are associated with 'mining'?
findAssocs(tdm, "datascience", 0.30)
## $datascience
## numeric(0)
#plot network

#plot(tdm, term = freq.terms, corThreshold = 0.15, weighting = T,attrs=list(node=list(fillcolor="cyan")))
plot(tdm, term = freq.terms, corThreshold = 0.20, weighting = T,attrs=list(node=list(label="foo", fillcolor="lightgreen",fontsize=24,height=1.8,width=1.8),edge=list(color="cyan",width="0.4")))

## Part2 wordcloud


# define tdm as matrix
m = as.matrix(tdm)
# get word counts in decreasing order
word_freqs = sort(rowSums(m), decreasing=TRUE) 
# create a data frame with words and their frequencies
dm = data.frame(word=names(word_freqs), freq=word_freqs)

# plot wordcloud
wordcloud(dm$word, dm$freq, random.order=FALSE, colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))
## Warning in wordcloud(dm$word, dm$freq, random.order = FALSE, colors =
## brewer.pal(8, : machinelearning could not be fit on page. It will not be

##Part3: Clustering 


# remove sparse terms
tdm2 <- removeSparseTerms(tdm, sparse = 0.96)

m2 <- as.matrix(tdm2)

# cluster terms
distMatrix <- dist(scale(m2))
fit <- hclust(distMatrix, method = "ward")
## The "ward" method has been renamed to "ward.D"; note new "ward.D2"
#plot the cluster
plot(fit)
rect.hclust(fit, k = 5) 

## Part4 : TOPIC MODELLING
#extract tweets again as we need mor number of tweets here.

mach_tweets = searchTwitter("#machinelearning", n=3200, lang="en")

# convert tweets to a data frame
machtweets.df <- twListToDF(mach_tweets)

#Extract the text from the tweets in a vector
mach_text = sapply(mach_tweets, function(x) x$getText())

#Construct the lexical Corpus and the Term Document Matrix
#function Corpus to create the corpus, and the function VectorSource to indicate that the text is in the character vector mach_text

mach_corpus = Corpus(VectorSource(mach_text))

## create document term matrix applying some transformations
MyCorpus <- tm_map(mach_corpus,
                   content_transformer(function(x) iconv(x, to='UTF-8-MAC', sub='byte')),
                   mc.cores=1)
tdm = TermDocumentMatrix(MyCorpus,control = list(removePunctuation = TRUE,stopwords = c("machine", "learning", "available", "via",stopwords("english")),removeNumbers = TRUE, tolower = TRUE))


dtm <- as.DocumentTermMatrix(tdm)

library(topicmodels)
library(data.table)
lda <- LDA(dtm, k = 8)
term <- terms(lda, 4)
term <- apply(term, MARGIN = 2, paste, collapse = ", ")
topic <- topics(lda, 1)
topics <- data.frame(date=as.IDate(machtweets.df$created), topic)
qplot(date, ..count.., data=topics, geom="density",fill=term[topic], position="stack")
